Why this workshop?¶

  • Helping beginners or long-time matlab users to make the step towards python
  • Synergy effects: shared tools and methods more efficient research
  • Open-source (including Python) is the future of scientific research (keyword: open science)

What will this workshop NOT be?¶

  • a course about the syntax of Python
  • a Matlab/IDL/R bashing show
  • a monologue

Switching to python: benefits¶

  • free and open-source
  • powerful, all-purpose language with a great syntax
  • scientific ecosystem
  • huge user-base (including ACINN)
  • "no-risk investment": python is going to stay for a while

Switching to python: drawbacks¶

  • steep learning curve
  • your existing tools will be difficult to translate
  • many (many) tools: not easy to know which to use

The three stages of the transition¶

Avoiding pitfalls¶

  • be patient: do not expect to be productive on the first day (and also not on the first week...)
  • DO NOT translate your existing code: pick a new project instead (i.e. for a new dataset you are analysing, a new paper you are writing)
  • Get some help before getting frustrated
  • Python is no golden egg: a transition must be carefully planned and might not always be the best move for your project/career/etc.

Getting started with Python¶

Major differences with other languages¶

  • No "all-in-one" development environment like Matlab
  • Out of the box, Python is no good

from scipy.interpolate import interp1d
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
x = np.linspace(0, 10, num=11, endpoint=True)
y = np.cos(-x**2/9.0)
f1 = interp1d(x, y)
f2 = interp1d(x, y, kind='cubic')
xnew = np.linspace(0, 10, 101, endpoint=True)
plt.plot(x, y, 'o', xnew, f1(xnew), '-', xnew, f2(xnew), '--')
plt.legend(['data', 'linear', 'cubic'], loc='best');
